# Code graph tool routing — REQUIRED for relational queries

**MANDATORY behavior:** when the user asks a relational code question (callers, callees, call chain, importers, class hierarchy, dead code, complexity, decorators, arguments), **the FIRST tool call MUST be a `CodeGraphContext` MCP tool** (e.g. `mcp_user-CodeGraphContext_analyze_code_relationships`). Do NOT use `Grep`, `Glob`, `Read`, or `SemanticSearch` first for these questions. Only fall back to grep if a CGC tool returns an explicit error or empty result.

The `CodeGraphContext` MCP server indexes repos you ran `codegraphcontext index` on. Backend is **Neo4j 5.21** in local Docker (`cgc-neo4j`, bolt `127.0.0.1:7687`, browser `http://localhost:7474`).

## Required routing for relational questions

| Question shape | CGC tool | Notes |
|----|----|----|
| "who calls X" (direct callers, default) | `analyze_code_relationships` (`find_callers`) | one hop, fast |
| "all transitive callers of X" (only if explicitly asked) | `analyze_code_relationships` (`find_all_callers`) | unbounded `[:CALLS*]` — slow on hot symbols; can hit tx timeout. Prefer `call_chain` with known endpoints. |
| "what does X call" (direct callees) | `analyze_code_relationships` (`find_callees`) | one hop |
| "trace from X to Y" | `analyze_code_relationships` (`call_chain`) | bounded path between two named functions |
| "who imports X", "module deps" | `analyze_code_relationships` (`find_importers` / `module_deps`) | import graph |
| "class hierarchy", "subclasses", "overrides" | `analyze_code_relationships` (`class_hierarchy` / `overrides`) | inheritance |
| "where is symbol X defined?" | `find_code` | symbol lookup |
| "is this dead code?" | `analyze_code_relationships` (`dead_code`) or `find_dead_code` | unused functions |
| "most complex / hot-spots" | `find_most_complex_functions`, `calculate_cyclomatic_complexity` | complexity |
| "functions with decorator X / argument Y" | `analyze_code_relationships` (`find_functions_by_decorator` / `find_functions_by_argument`) | filtered queries |

## Keep using grep / Glob / Read when

- Literal string or regex in configs, YAML, env, markdown, SQL.
- Finding files by name pattern.
- Sources CGC does not parse (e.g. some frameworks, Dockerfile, Terraform) or file types without parsers in your CGC version.
- Reading a path you already know.

## SemanticSearch

Useful for fuzzy "how does X work" without a symbol name. Once you have a concrete symbol, prefer CGC.

## Worked examples

GOOD — relational, FIRST action is the MCP tool, not grep:

- User: "What functions call `some_helper`?"
  Assistant FIRST tool call: `analyze_code_relationships` with `query_type=find_callers`, `target=some_helper`.
  (Do **not** start with `Grep` for `some_helper`. Do **not** Glob the MCP descriptor folder — call the tool directly.)
- "Call chain from `api.handlers.foo` to `db.session`."
  -> `query_type=call_chain`.
- "Most complex functions in this package?"
  -> `find_most_complex_functions`.

ANTI-PATTERN — do not do this:

- User: "Who calls X?" -> Assistant runs `Grep` for `X`. **Wrong.** Call `analyze_code_relationships find_callers` first; only fall back to grep if it errors.

DANGER — transitive only when user explicitly wants it:

- `find_all_callers` / `find_all_callees` use unbounded `[:CALLS*]`. Hot symbols (fixtures, session deps, logging helpers) can hit Neo4j transaction timeout. Default "who calls X" -> `find_callers`.

BAD — literal / file:

- Scattered `TODO` strings -> `Grep`.
- Env var names, not symbols -> `Grep`.

## Operational

- Staleness: graph reflects last `codegraphcontext index` / `make cgc-index`. Recently edited files may need re-index or grep.
- Anything never indexed is invisible to CGC.
- Neo4j: `~/.codegraphcontext/neo4j/` (compose + `.password`). Manage via **cursor-cgc** repo: `make cgc-up`, `make cgc-down`, etc. Credentials also in `~/.codegraphcontext/.env`.
- Prefer indexing when other clients are not hammering the DB.
- Query timeout defaults to 30s in compose (`NEO4J_db_transaction_timeout`). Timeout errors are expected on bad queries; use `find_callers` or narrow the question.
